Protesters gather on the beach against Shell's seismic survey. eNCA/Monique Mortlock JOHANNESBURG - Another seismic survey is due to begin from South Africa's Cape Point to Namibia. This is according to the Coastal Justice Network (CJN). Australian company, Searcher Goedata was granted a permit to conduct the exploration in 2021. READ: Court halts Shell’s seismic survey off the Wild Coast The survey is being conducted in an area where sixteen other companies have exploration rights. Small scale fisher communities and their lawyers have written to Minerals and Energy Minister Gwede Mantashe outlining grave concerns over the granting of the license. The CJN says there is scant information available about the application and its approval. Adding that fishing communities were not consulted. Two weeks after a court stalled Shell’s seismic surveys, another will begin this weekend, according to the Coastal Justice Network. Australian company, Searcher Geodata was granted a permit to conduct exploration off SA's west coast from Cape Point to Namibia in 2021. #DStv403 pic.twitter.com/O0DT6wJqh5